<h1>Ordered Sets</h1>

<p>The concept of a partial order generalizes the inequality ‚â§ on ‚Ñ§ and ‚Ñù to a ordering of objects in a set.</p>

<p><b>Definition 1.3.1</b>. A <i>relation</i> on a set <i>S</i> is a subset <i>R</i> of the cartesian product <i>S</i> x <i>S</i>. The relation <i>R</i> is an <i>ordering</i> (or partial order) of <i>S</i> provided that it obeys the following axioms, where we use the notations <i>s</i> ‚âº <i>t</i> to signal that (<i>s,t</i>) &in; <i>R</i>, and <i>s</i> ‚â∫ <i>t</i> to mean that  <i>s</i> ‚âº <i>t</i> and <i>s</i> &ne; <i>t</i>:</p>

<ol type="a">
	<li><p><i>Reflexivity</i>.  <i>s</i> ‚âº <i>s</i> for each <i>s</i> &in; <i>S</i>;</p></li>
	<li><p><i>Antisymmetry</i>. If, for a pair of elements <i>s</i> and <i>t</i> in <i>S</i>, we have  <i>s</i> ‚âº <i>t</i> and  <i>t</i> ‚âº <i>s</i>, then <i>s</i> = <i>t</i>;</p></li>
	<li><p><i>Transitivity</i>. If, for a triple <i>s, t, u</i> &in; <i>S</i>, we have  <i>s</i> ‚âº <i>t</i> and  <i>t</i> ‚âº <i>u</i>, then  <i>s</i> ‚âº <i>u</i>.</p></li>
</ol>

<p>If in addition an ordering  ‚âº of <i>S</i> satisfies</p>

<div class="eq">
<p><i>Trichotomy</i>. If <i>s,t</i> &in; <i>S</i> then <i>s</i> ‚â∫ <i>t</i> or <i>t</i> ‚â∫ <i>s</i> or <i>s</i> = <i>t</i></p>
</div>

<p>then the ordering is called <b>total order</b>.&emsp;‚ñ°</p>

<p><b>Note</b>. The order relation is not an <a href="relations.html#eq">equivlance relation</a> (it isn't symmetric). The symmetric property is replaced by the antisymmetric property.</p>

<p><b>Definition 1.3.2</b>. A pair (<i>A</i>, ‚âº), where <i>A</i> is a set and ‚âº is a partial order on <i>A</i> is often succinctly called a <i>poset</i>. &emsp;‚ñ°</p>

<p>The adjective <i>partial</i> means that, in a general poset (<i>A</i>, ‚âº), given two arbitrary elements <i>a, b</i> ‚àà <i>A</i>, it is possible that neither <i>a</i> ‚âº <i>b</i> nor <i>b</i> ‚âº <i>a</i>; in this case we say that <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> are not <i>comparable</i>.</p>

<p>The posets (‚Ñï, ‚â§) and (‚Ñù, ‚â§) are total orders. Many posets are not total orders as the following examples illustrate:</p>

<p><b>Example 1.3.3.</b> Consider the donor relation ‚Üí defined on the set of blood types <i>X</i> = {<i>o, a, b, ab</i>}. Then ‚Üí is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive. This shows that (<i>X</i>, ‚Üí) is a poset. Note that <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> are not comparable, meaning that neither can donate to the other. &emsp;‚ñ†</p>

<p><b>Example 1.3.4</b>. In the power set ùí´(<i>X</i>) the relations &subseteq; as &supseteq; are partial orders but not a total orders; For example let <i>A</i> = ùí´(<i>X</i>) where <i>X</i> = {<i>a,b,c</i>} we have</p> 

<div class="eq">
<p>ùí´(<i>X</i>) = {√ò, {<i>a</i>}, {<i>b</i>}, {<i>c</i>}, {<i>a,b</i>}, {<i>a,c</i>}, {<i>b,c</i>}, {<i>a,b,c</i>}}</p>
</div>

<p>Trichotomy does not hold as neither {<i>a</i>} ‚äÜ {<i>b</i>}, {<i>b</i>} ‚äÜ {<i>a</i>} or {<i>a</i>} = {<i>b</i>} holds.&emsp;‚ñ†</p>

<p><b>Definition 1.3.5</b>. Let (<i>A</i>, ‚âº) be a poset. If for some pair {<i>a, b</i>} of distinct elements, either <i>a</i> ‚âº <i>b</i> or <i>b</i> ‚âº <i>a</i> then we say that <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> are <b>comparable</b>; otherwise <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> are called <b>incomparable</b>. A partial order in which every pair of elements is comparable is called a <b>total order</b>.&emsp;‚ñ°</p>

<p>In example 1.3.4 the sets {<i>a</i>} and {<i>b</i>} are <i>incomparable</i>.</pre>

<p><b>Example 1.3.6.</b> Consider the relation ‚â§ on ‚Ñ§. For all <i>x</i> ‚àà ‚Ñ§, <i>x</i> ‚â§ <i>x</i> so ‚â§ is reflexive. For all <i>x, y</i> ‚àà ‚Ñ§, if <i>x</i> ‚â§ <i>y</i> and <i>y</i> ‚â§ <i>x</i>, then <i>x</i> = <i>y</i> and hence ‚â§ is antisymmetric. It is also true that <i>x</i> ‚â§ <i>y</i> and <i>y</i> ‚â§ <i>z</i> implies that <i>x</i> ‚â§ <i>z</i> and hence ‚â§ is transitive. Since for all <i>x,y</i> in ‚Ñ§, <i>x</i> &le; <i>y</i> or <i>y</i> &le; <i>x</i>. Thus, the inequality ‚â§ on ‚Ñ§ is a total order. &emsp;‚ñ†</p>

<p>Note that ‚â• is also a partial order on ‚Ñ§ but that the strict inequalities < and > are not. The inequality < is not reflexive though it is both antisymmetric and transitive. (< is antisymmetric because there do not exist any <i>x, y</i> ‚àà ‚Ñ§ such that <i>x</i>.</p>

<p>Motivated by the notations for inequalities over ‚Ñ§, we use the symbol ‚â∫ to mean</p>

<div class="eq">
<p><i>x</i> ‚â∫ <i>y</i> ‚áê‚áí <i>x</i> ‚âº <i>y</i> and <i>x</i> &ne; <i>y</i></p>
</div>

<p>and the symbol ‚äÄ to mean that it is not true that <i>x</i> ‚âº <i>y</i>.</p>

